## The Integration Problem

Every AI application faces the same challenge: connecting language models to external data and tools. Before MCP, this meant:

- Custom integration code for every tool
- Different patterns for each AI provider
- Brittle connections that break with updates
- Duplicated effort across projects

Anthopic's Model Context Protocol (MCP) solves this by providing a universal standard—think USB-C for AI.

## What is MCP?

MCP is an open protocol that standardizes how AI models connect to external systems. It defines:

- **Resources**: Data the AI can read (files, databases, APIs)
- **Tools**: Actions the AI can perform (execute code, send emails, query systems)
- **Prompts**: Reusable prompt templates
- **Sampling**: How the AI generates responses

### The Architecture

```
┌─────────────────┐     MCP Protocol     ┌─────────────────┐
│   AI Client     │ ◄──────────────────► │   MCP Server    │
│  (Claude, etc)  │                      │  (Your Tools)   │
└─────────────────┘                      └─────────────────┘
        │                                        │
        │                                        │
   Uses tools                              Exposes tools
   and resources                           and resources
```

The AI client speaks MCP to any compatible server, regardless of what that server actually does.

## Building Your First MCP Server

Let's create a simple MCP server that provides weather data:

```typescript
import { Server } from "@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/index.js";
import { StdioServerTransport } from "@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/server/stdio.js";

const server = new Server(
  {
    name: "weather-server",
    version: "1.0.0",
  },
  {
    capabilities: {
      tools: {},
      resources: {},
    },
  }
);

// Define a tool
server.setRequestHandler("tools/list", async () => ({
  tools: [
    {
      name: "get_weather",
      description: "Get current weather for a city",
      inputSchema: {
        type: "object",
        properties: {
          city: {
            type: "string",
            description: "City name",
          },
        },
        required: ["city"],
      },
    },
  ],
}));

// Handle tool calls
server.setRequestHandler("tools/call", async (request) => {
  if (request.params.name === "get_weather") {
    const city = request.params.arguments.city;
    const weather = await fetchWeatherAPI(city);
    return {
      content: [
        {
          type: "text",
          text: JSON.stringify(weather),
        },
      ],
    };
  }
});

// Start server
const transport = new StdioServerTransport();
await server.connect(transport);
```

## Resources vs Tools

### Resources (Read-Only Data)

Resources are data sources the AI can query:

```typescript
server.setRequestHandler("resources/list", async () => ({
  resources: [
    {
      uri: "file:///config/settings.json",
      name: "Application Settings",
      mimeType: "application/json",
    },
    {
      uri: "db://users/schema",
      name: "User Database Schema",
      mimeType: "text/plain",
    },
  ],
}));

server.setRequestHandler("resources/read", async (request) => {
  const { uri } = request.params;
  // Return the resource content
  return {
    contents: [
      {
        uri,
        mimeType: "application/json",
        text: JSON.stringify(await loadResource(uri)),
      },
    ],
  };
});
```

### Tools (Actions)

Tools let the AI perform actions:

```typescript
const tools = [
  {
    name: "send_email",
    description: "Send an email to a recipient",
    inputSchema: {
      type: "object",
      properties: {
        to: { type: "string" },
        subject: { type: "string" },
        body: { type: "string" },
      },
      required: ["to", "subject", "body"],
    },
  },
  {
    name: "create_calendar_event",
    description: "Schedule a calendar event",
    inputSchema: {
      type: "object",
      properties: {
        title: { type: "string" },
        datetime: { type: "string", format: "date-time" },
        duration_minutes: { type: "number" },
      },
      required: ["title", "datetime"],
    },
  },
];
```

## Popular MCP Servers

The MCP ecosystem has exploded with pre-built servers:

### Official Servers

- **Filesystem**: Read/write local files
- **Git**: Repository operations
- **PostgreSQL/SQLite**: Database access
- **Puppeteer**: Web automation
- **Slack**: Messaging integration

### Community Servers

- **Notion**: Document management
- **Linear**: Issue tracking
- **Figma**: Design file access
- **AWS**: Cloud service management
- **Kubernetes**: Cluster operations

## Integrating MCP with Your AI App

### Claude Desktop

Add servers to your `claude_desktop_config.json`:

```json
{
  "mcpServers": {
    "weather": {
      "command": "node",
      "args": ["/path/to/weather-server/index.js"]
    },
    "filesystem": {
      "command": "npx",
      "args": ["-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem", "/Users/me/projects"]
    }
  }
}
```

### Programmatic Usage

```typescript
import { Client } from "@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/client/index.js";
import { StdioClientTransport } from "@modelcontextprotocol/sdk/client/stdio.js";

const transport = new StdioClientTransport({
  command: "node",
  args: ["./weather-server/index.js"],
});

const client = new Client(
  {
    name: "my-app",
    version: "1.0.0",
  },
  {
    capabilities: {},
  }
);

await client.connect(transport);

// List available tools
const tools = await client.request({ method: "tools/list" }, {});

// Call a tool
const result = await client.request(
  { method: "tools/call" },
  {
    name: "get_weather",
    arguments: { city: "San Francisco" },
  }
);
```

## Security Considerations

### Principle of Least Privilege

Only expose what's necessary:

```typescript
// ❌ Too permissive
const tools = [{ name: "execute_shell", description: "Run any shell command" }];

// ✅ Scoped appropriately
const tools = [
  { name: "list_directory", description: "List files in allowed directories" },
  { name: "read_file", description: "Read files in the project folder" },
];
```

### Input Validation

Always validate inputs:

```typescript
server.setRequestHandler("tools/call", async (request) => {
  const { city } = request.params.arguments;

  // Validate input
  if (typeof city !== 'string' || city.length > 100) {
    throw new Error("Invalid city parameter");
  }

  // Sanitize for API call
  const sanitizedCity = city.replace(/[^a-zA-Z\s-]/g, '');

  return fetchWeather(sanitizedCity);
});
```

### Audit Logging

```typescript
server.setRequestHandler("tools/call", async (request) => {
  const { name, arguments: args } = request.params;

  // Log all tool invocations
  logger.info("Tool invocation", {
    tool: name,
    arguments: args,
    timestamp: new Date().toISOString(),
  });

  return executeToolSafely(name, args);
});
```

## MCP vs Function Calling vs Plugins

| Feature | MCP | Function Calling | ChatGPT Plugins |
|---------|-----|------------------|------------------|
| Provider agnostic | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ |
| Open standard | ✅ | Varies | ❌ |
| Bidirectional | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ |
| Resource access | ✅ | ❌ | Limited |
| Local execution | ✅ | ❌ | ❌ |

## Best Practices

### 1. Clear Descriptions

AI models rely on descriptions to use tools correctly:

```typescript
// ❌ Vague
{ name: "process", description: "Process data" }

// ✅ Specific
{
  name: "analyze_sentiment",
  description: "Analyze the sentiment of text. Returns a score from -1 (negative) to 1 (positive) with confidence level."
}
```

### 2. Structured Errors

```typescript
server.setRequestHandler("tools/call", async (request) => {
  try {
    return await executeTool(request);
  } catch (error) {
    return {
      content: [{
        type: "text",
        text: JSON.stringify({
          error: true,
          message: error.message,
          code: error.code,
          suggestion: "Check if the city name is spelled correctly"
        })
      }],
      isError: true
    };
  }
});
```

### 3. Batch Operations

When possible, support batch operations:

```typescript
{
  name: "get_weather_batch",
  description: "Get weather for multiple cities at once",
  inputSchema: {
    type: "object",
    properties: {
      cities: {
        type: "array",
        items: { type: "string" },
        maxItems: 10
      }
    }
  }
}
```

## The Future of MCP

Anthopic is actively developing MCP with:

- **Streaming support** for long-running operations
- **Authentication standards** for secure multi-tenant servers
- **Discovery protocols** for finding available servers
- **Versioning** for backward compatibility

As more AI providers adopt MCP, we're moving toward a world where integrations are truly write-once, use-anywhere.

## Conclusion

MCP represents a maturing of the AI ecosystem. Instead of fragmented, provider-specific integrations, we're getting a universal standard that benefits everyone—developers, users, and AI providers alike.

If you're building AI applications, adopting MCP now positions you well for the future of AI integration.

