## React Has Changed

If you learned React before 2024, much of what you know needs updating. React 19 isn't just an incremental update—it's a fundamental shift in how we think about building web applications.

The headline features:

- **Server Components** are now the default
- **Actions** replace traditional form handling
- **use()** hook for async data
- **Improved hydration** and streaming
- **Native metadata** support

Let's break down what this means for your code.

## Server Components: The New Default

### The Mental Model Shift

Previously, React ran entirely in the browser. Now, React components can run on the server, client, or both.

```tsx
// This component runs ONLY on the server
// No "use client" directive = Server Component

async function ProductPage({ id }: { id: string }) {
  // Direct database access! No API needed
  const product = await db.product.findUnique({ where: { id } });

  // This code never ships to the browser
  const recommendations = await ml.getRecommendations(product);

  return (
    <main>
      <h1>{product.name}</h1>
      <p>{product.description}</p>
      <AddToCartButton productId={id} /> {/* Client Component */}
      <Recommendations items={recommendations} />
    </main>
  );
}
```

### What Server Components Can Do

- Access databases directly
- Read files from the filesystem
- Use server-only secrets
- Import heavy dependencies without client bundle cost
- Render content that doesn't need interactivity

### What Server Components Cannot Do

- Use `useState`, `useEffect`, or any client hooks
- Access browser APIs (window, document, localStorage)
- Use event handlers (onClick, onChange, etc.)
- Use context that requires client-side state

## Client Components: When You Need Interactivity

Add `"use client"` at the top to make a component run in the browser:

```tsx
"use client";

import { useState } from "react";

function AddToCartButton({ productId }: { productId: string }) {
  const [loading, setLoading] = useState(false);
  const [added, setAdded] = useState(false);

  const handleClick = async () => {
    setLoading(true);
    await addToCart(productId);
    setAdded(true);
    setLoading(false);
  };

  return (
    <button onClick={handleClick} disabled={loading}>
      {added ? "Added ✓" : loading ? "Adding..." : "Add to Cart"}
    </button>
  );
}
```

### The Composition Pattern

The key insight: Client Components can render Server Components passed as children:

```tsx
// layout.tsx (Server Component)
import { ClientShell } from "./ClientShell";
import { ServerContent } from "./ServerContent";

export default function Layout({ children }) {
  return (
    <ClientShell> {/* Client: handles animations, state */}
      <ServerContent /> {/* Server: fetches data */}
      {children}
    </ClientShell>
  );
}
```

```tsx
// ClientShell.tsx
"use client";

import { motion } from "framer-motion";

export function ClientShell({ children }) {
  return (
    <motion.div initial={{ opacity: 0 }} animate={{ opacity: 1 }}>
      {children} {/* Server Components render here */}
    </motion.div>
  );
}
```

## Actions: The New Form Handling

Forget `e.preventDefault()` and manual fetch calls. Actions handle form submissions:

```tsx
// Server Action
async function createPost(formData: FormData) {
  "use server";

  const title = formData.get("title") as string;
  const content = formData.get("content") as string;

  // Validate
  if (!title || !content) {
    return { error: "Title and content required" };
  }

  // Save to database
  const post = await db.post.create({
    data: { title, content },
  });

  // Revalidate and redirect
  revalidatePath("/posts");
  redirect(`/posts/${post.id}`);
}

// Component using the action
function NewPostForm() {
  return (
    <form action={createPost}>
      <input name="title" required />
      <textarea name="content" required />
      <button type="submit">Create Post</button>
    </form>
  );
}
```

### useActionState for Complex Forms

```tsx
"use client";

import { useActionState } from "react";

function LoginForm() {
  const [state, formAction, isPending] = useActionState(
    loginAction,
    { error: null }
  );

  return (
    <form action={formAction}>
      <input name="email" type="email" required />
      <input name="password" type="password" required />
      {state.error && <p className="error">{state.error}</p>}
      <button disabled={isPending}>
        {isPending ? "Logging in..." : "Login"}
      </button>
    </form>
  );
}
```

### useOptimistic for Instant Feedback

```tsx
"use client";

import { useOptimistic } from "react";

function TodoList({ todos }: { todos: Todo[] }) {
  const [optimisticTodos, addOptimisticTodo] = useOptimistic(
    todos,
    (state, newTodo: Todo) => [...state, newTodo]
  );

  async function addTodo(formData: FormData) {
    const text = formData.get("text") as string;

    // Immediately show the new todo
    addOptimisticTodo({ id: crypto.randomUUID(), text, pending: true });

    // Actually save it
    await createTodo(text);
  }

  return (
    <>
      <ul>
        {optimisticTodos.map((todo) => (
          <li key={todo.id} style={{ opacity: todo.pending ? 0.5 : 1 }}>
            {todo.text}
          </li>
        ))}
      </ul>
      <form action={addTodo}>
        <input name="text" />
        <button>Add</button>
      </form>
    </>
  );
}
```

## The use() Hook

Read promises and context in a new way:

```tsx
import { use, Suspense } from "react";

async function fetchUser(id: string) {
  const res = await fetch(`/api/users/${id}`);
  return res.json();
}

function UserProfile({ userPromise }: { userPromise: Promise<User> }) {
  // use() unwraps the promise
  const user = use(userPromise);

  return (
    <div>
      <h1>{user.name}</h1>
      <p>{user.email}</p>
    </div>
  );
}

// Usage
function Page({ userId }: { userId: string }) {
  // Start fetching immediately
  const userPromise = fetchUser(userId);

  return (
    <Suspense fallback={<Skeleton />}>
      <UserProfile userPromise={userPromise} />
    </Suspense>
  );
}
```

## Data Fetching Patterns

### Pattern 1: Fetch in Server Component

```tsx
// The simplest pattern - fetch where you need data
async function Dashboard() {
  const [user, stats, notifications] = await Promise.all([
    getUser(),
    getStats(),
    getNotifications(),
  ]);

  return (
    <div>
      <Header user={user} />
      <Stats data={stats} />
      <Notifications items={notifications} />
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Pattern 2: Streaming with Suspense

```tsx
import { Suspense } from "react";

async function Page() {
  return (
    <div>
      {/* Renders immediately */}
      <Header />

      {/* Streams in when ready */}
      <Suspense fallback={<StatsSkeleton />}>
        <Stats />
      </Suspense>

      <Suspense fallback={<FeedSkeleton />}>
        <Feed />
      </Suspense>
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Pattern 3: Parallel Data Fetching

```tsx
async function ProductPage({ id }: { id: string }) {
  // Start all fetches simultaneously
  const productPromise = getProduct(id);
  const reviewsPromise = getReviews(id);
  const relatedPromise = getRelated(id);

  // Await them together
  const [product, reviews, related] = await Promise.all([
    productPromise,
    reviewsPromise,
    relatedPromise,
  ]);

  return <>{/* render */}</>;
}
```

## Common Mistakes to Avoid

### Mistake 1: Unnecessary Client Components

```tsx
// ❌ This doesn't need to be a client component
"use client";
function ProductCard({ product }) {
  return (
    <div>
      <h2>{product.name}</h2>
      <p>{product.price}</p>
    </div>
  );
}

// ✅ Keep it as a Server Component
function ProductCard({ product }) {
  return (
    <div>
      <h2>{product.name}</h2>
      <p>{product.price}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

### Mistake 2: Prop Drilling Server Data

```tsx
// ❌ Passing data through many components
async function Page() {
  const user = await getUser();
  return <Layout user={user}><Content user={user} /></Layout>;
}

// ✅ Fetch where you need it
async function Header() {
  const user = await getUser(); // Deduplicated automatically
  return <nav>{user.name}</nav>;
}

async function Sidebar() {
  const user = await getUser(); // Same request, cached
  return <aside>{user.email}</aside>;
}
```

### Mistake 3: Blocking Renders

```tsx
// ❌ Sequential fetches block each other
async function Page() {
  const user = await getUser();
  const posts = await getPosts(); // Waits for user to finish
  const comments = await getComments(); // Waits for posts
}

// ✅ Parallel fetches
async function Page() {
  const [user, posts, comments] = await Promise.all([
    getUser(),
    getPosts(),
    getComments(),
  ]);
}
```

## Migration Strategy

Moving an existing React app to React 19:

### Step 1: Update Dependencies

```bash
npm install react@19 react-dom@19
```

### Step 2: Audit Client Components

Review every `useState` and `useEffect`. Many can become Server Components.

### Step 3: Convert Data Fetching

Replace `useEffect` + `fetch` with async Server Components.

### Step 4: Adopt Actions

Convert form handlers to Server Actions.

### Step 5: Add Suspense Boundaries

Wrap async components for better loading states.

## Conclusion

React 19 is the biggest shift since hooks. The mental model change—thinking about where code runs—takes time to internalize. But the benefits are substantial:

- Smaller client bundles
- Better performance
- Simpler data fetching
- Enhanced security
- Improved DX

The future of React is hybrid, and it's already here.

